# Internationalization and Itinerary Expansion Plan

This plan details how we will improve the initialization of the itinerary and add support for English and Traditional Chinese (zh-TW).

## Goal
1. Expand the `data.ts` file to fully populate all POIs based on the initial user prompt (adding all missing locations for Hakone, Nara, Osaka, Fukuoka, and Busan).
2. Add internationalization (i18n) to support both English (en) and Traditional Chinese (zh-TW) for the application UI and the itinerary content.

## Proposed Changes

### Setup & Dependencies
- Install `i18next` and `react-i18next` to handle translations easily.

### i18n Configuration
- Create `src/i18n.ts` to initialize `react-i18next` with `en` and `zh-TW` translations.
- Store the user's language preference in `localStorage` so it persists between reloads.
- Add a Language Switcher component in the app header to toggle between English and 繁體中文.

### Itinerary Expansion & Translation
- Update `src/data.ts` to include translation keys or bilingual objects for all POIs and daily descriptions.
- Instead of just `name: string`, `desc: string`, we will update the `POI` interface to `name: { en: string; zh: string }` and `desc: { en: string; zh: string }`.
- Update the `DayItinerary` interface similarly to support `title` and `customItems` in both languages.
- Expand the POI list to include all specific places mentioned in the original 5-week itinerary (e.g., Harajuku, Omotesando, Hakone ropeway, Nishiki Market, Canal City Hakata, etc.).

### UI Refactoring
- Wrap all hardcoded text strings in `App.tsx`, `Dashboard.tsx`, `Itinerary.tsx`, `MapView.tsx`, and `Notes.tsx` with the `t()` function from `react-i18next`.
- Update components to read from the bilingual POI/Itinerary data based on the current active language.

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]  
> Because the `data.ts` expansion requires updating the data structure to support both English and Traditional Chinese natively (e.g., changing `name: "Ueno Park"` to `name: { en: "Ueno Park", zh: "上野公園" }`), this will break the existing local storage data for anyone who already loaded the app. Since the app is in development, I will just reset the `zustand` store version or prompt the app to re-initialize the itinerary. Are you okay with this approach?

## Open Questions

> [!WARNING]  
> Do you want the user's custom added items (which they type into the app) to be translated automatically? (Note: Without an external backend/AI API key, the app cannot translate user input automatically, so user-added custom items will remain in the language they were typed in). I assume this is acceptable?
